<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWS BITES: IT'S BOTTLENECK AND BOTTLENECK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN BERGER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After a century of being the most heavily planted grape in California, 
Zinfandel was nosed out by Cabernet in 1992, 34,567 acres to 34,142.The race is 
still still on, though. Even though 773 acres of Cabernet were planted last 
year, the state Cabernet total only reached 34,933 acres because vines infested 
with the new strain of root louse (phylloxera) and other ailments were taken 
out. Meanwhile, Zinfandel climbed to 35,341 acres. DAN BERGER 
</P>
