<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY HALL ROUNDUP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 BEVERLY HILLS: The City Council just may give its members an additional year 
in office. 
</P>
<P>
 Council members this week said they would consider giving themselves another 
11 months in office because of a change in the 1996 election schedule. 
</P>
<P>
 The issue arose after the state Legislature changed the date of the California 
presidential primary from June, 1996, to March 26, 1996, so that it is held 
earlier in the presidential campaign. The Legislature also authorized cities to 
reschedule general municipal elections. 
</P>
<P>
 The Los Angeles County Registrar-Recorder's office, which oversees the 
elections, has asked municipalities that receive its help to reschedule the 
date of local elections from April, 1996, so that it is not so close to the 
primary. 
</P>
<P>
 The county has said it would be unavailable to help Beverly Hills conduct the 
April 9, 1996, municipal election because of the date's proximity to the 
presidential primary. 
</P>
<P>
 City officials said they require the county's aid to conduct elections and 
would like to reschedule the city election to coincide with an existing 
county-run election. The possibilities are Nov. 8, 1996, and March 4, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
 November would not be good, officials said, because voters may confuse issues 
with the Beverly Hills Board of Education election already scheduled for that 
date, council members said. 
</P>
<P>
 The council will vote June 21 on whether to hold the election in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
 The terms of Beverly Hills Mayor Vicki Reynolds and councilmen Allan Alexander 
and Tom Levyn are scheduled to expire April 9, 1996. If the date is changed to 
March 4, 1997, Levyn, who would be the senior council member then, could rotate 
into the mayoral position without facing reelection. The two council members 
elected this year, MeraLee Goldman and Les Bronte, would have their terms 
extended from April, 1998, to March, 1999. MEETINGS NEXT WEEK 
</P>
<P>
 * Beverly Hills: 7:30 p.m. Tuesday, 450 Crescent Drive, (310) 285-2400. 
</P>
<P>
 * Culver City: 7 p.m. Monday, Interim City Hall, Trailer No. 1, 4095 Overland 
Ave., (310) 202-5851. 
</P>
<P>
 * Los Angeles: 10 a.m. Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday, 200 N. Spring St., (213) 
485-3126. 
</P>
<P>
 * Malibu: 6:30 p.m. Monday, Hughes Laboratory, 3011 Malibu Canyon Road, (310) 
456-2489. 
</P>
<P>
 * Santa Monica: 6:30 p.m. Tuesday, 1685 Main St., (310) 393-9975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
