<HEADLINE>
<P>
WESTSIDE COVER STORY; THE MAGIC TOUCH; THE LANDMARK MAGIC CASTLE TURNS TO A 
WITCH'S BREW OF MARKETING TO MAKE A HUGE DEBT DISAPPEAR. THE CLUB IS BETTER 
RUN, BUT SOME NOW FEAR IT FOCUSES MORE ON MONEY THAN MAGIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN CRAY, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It commands a hilltop overlooking Hollywood, a Victorian landmark that for 
more than three decades has beckoned wizards the world over. Blackstone, 
Wilson, Henning and Copperfield are among the hundreds of illusionists who have 
been drawn into its elegant brass and mahogany halls, its dusty libraries and 
its vaudevillian theaters. There, they practiced the mind-boggling, the 
jaw-dropping, the flat-out spectacular. 
</P>
<P>
 But ask any member of the Magic Castle, and they will tell you the most 
astounding feat of magic ever performed in those halls was wiping out a 
half-million-dollar debt that only a year ago threatened to send the ghostly 
Victorian club to a fate no modern-day Merlin could have reversed. 
</P>
<P>
 "The club rallied, and we paid off all outstanding debts," says a relieved Al 
Davis, general manager at the Magic Castle, with a sigh. "As of now, we're in 
the black." 
</P>
<P>
 In the process of clearing the slate, however, the Magic Castle was forced to 
turn to a witch's brew of marketing that effectively transformed it into a very 
different place of business from the venerable private club that had survived 
for 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
 Once operated as a simple gathering spot for local magicians and magic buffs, 
today's Castle is run like a multimillion-dollar business, with all of its 
attendant benefits and drawbacks. Non-magicians' membership fees, for a decade 
only $220 a year, have been boosted nearly 50% -- to $325 -- as part of a major 
fund-raising effort to meet the club's operating budget of about $3 million a 
year. Gone are the sympathetic booking policies, where a magician with more 
heart than talent occasionally got a chance to perform in one of the magic 
community's finest venues. Missing most of all is a piece of the club's 
exclusivity, with large groups and corporations now able to rent the Castle on 
any given day and a governing board that has held preliminary discussions about 
opening the club to the public one night a week. 
</P>
<P>
 In its place is a club that is more professionally run and offers better 
entertainment for the casual guest, but which some magicians fear is focused 
more on money than magic. Under new Castle policies, most of the performers 
must be experienced club favorites. Only about 10% of the acts are new talent. 
</P>
<P>
 A financial analyst reviews all of the club's statements each month and Castle 
directors review the findings. With the addition of special theme nights, and 
even the possibility of establishing a gift shop, there is new hope that club 
membership will rise after nearly 10 years of holding steady at 5,000. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Castle was well-run before, but by people who were inexperienced with 
multimillion-dollar businesses," says Lewis Horwitz, an investment banker who 
last year became treasurer for the nonprofit Academy of Magical Arts, the group 
that operates the Magic Castle. "Sure, there are a lot of good business people 
who were on the board (in the past), but the academy grew to very substantial 
proportions, and then when the recession hit and people stopped going to dinner 
as much as they used to, the directors didn't want to cut anything out for the 
membership. Expenses stayed the same, while income went down, down, down." 
</P>
<P>
 At about the same time, the Castle's president, co-founder and business 
manager, Bill Larsen, was stricken with a lengthy illness and eventually died 
of a liver ailment in February, 1993. At the time of Larsen's death, the club 
had a $200,000 bank loan outstanding and faced $300,000 in additional bills. 
</P>
<P>
 "I came in and said, 'All right, you guys, this is what you have to do,' " 
says Horwitz, who believes the club's longtime focus on magic and service to 
its membership had the undesired effect of delaying belt-tightening. 
</P>
<P>
 Under Horwitz's direction, the academy's board ordered a 50% increase in 
membership dues -- for non-magicians -- and upped the entrance fee for new 
members from $800 to $900. In addition, the Castle's 5,000 members were asked 
to make a one-time contribution of $100 each and efforts to rent the Castle to 
private parties were stepped up, making the building available five days a week 
instead of two. 
</P>
<P>
 It was a sharp departure for a club that had grown out of one family's 
enthusiasm for magic. The Castle was founded in 1963 by Larsen, then an 
associate producer at CBS, and his brother, Milt Jr., a writer for the Truth or 
Consequences television show. The pair, fans of magic since they were children, 
found a home for their club in a hilltop mansion built in 1908, once a 
residence overlooking an orange grove. 
</P>
<P>
 "Lew Horwitz has done the greatest magic act I've ever seen, because he's been 
able to take what had been a very casual kind of operation and give it some 
very specific business responsibilities and parameters," says Harry Blackstone 
Jr., a new member of the Castle's board of directors and a performer at the 
Castle since first appearing there with his legendary father in the early 
1960s. "It needs to be run that way, and there are only a few who have to take 
that attitude, so therefore the others can just come in and enjoy it." 
</P>
<P>
 Cognizant of a skeptical membership, Castle management has been careful to 
avoid becoming too blatant about its newly adopted marketing practices. Michael 
Fleming, who heads up the Castle's efforts to persuade corporations and groups 
to rent the building for board meetings and other gatherings, says he has 
intentionally avoided running advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
 "We try to approach businesses on a low-key basis," Fleming says. "I wouldn't 
want to go outside of low-key, person-to-person contact. I talk to (Castle) 
members on the phone, tell them what we can do for them or their company. I 
mean, if a company is doing an instructional seminar, before the VP comes out, 
you have a magician loosen up the crowd and all of a sudden the VP becomes a 
lot more listenable." 
</P>
<P>
 Companies such as AT&T, Shell Oil and Northrop Management Assn. have paid from 
$25 to $70 a head (the price varies according to the scope of the event) to 
rent the Castle within the past several months. With a minimum group of 40 
people required to book the Castle, these efforts have resulted in income of 
several thousand dollars per booking. 
</P>
<P>
 The academy's management cites member donations and increased fees as reasons 
that the Castle was able to wipe out its debts, but several board members 
privately admit that it was the corporate parties that made the difference. 
</P>
<P>
 Complaints among magicians about the Castle's rental policies have been low. 
The same cannot be said for the informal discussions about whether the club 
should open to the public one night a week. 
</P>
<P>
 "It would cut into the exclusivity of the Castle," says Brian Gillis, a 
Redondo Beach magician who has appeared on the Tonight Show and performs at the 
Castle several times a year. "When I was out here from Tennessee, I'd tell 
someone I was working the Magic Castle and it was, 'Oh my god, can you get me 
in? Can you get me a pass?' It was really an exciting thing. If it opens to the 
public, it won't be like that. Right now it has a lot of prestige, and you get 
audiences that really appreciate the skill and the talent of what you're 
doing." 
</P>
<P>
 Most magicians agree, saying the Castle is the one place where they garner 
respect from an audience, rather than being viewed as con men who know a few 
card tricks. As a result, Milt Larsen Jr. says he would do everything he could 
to prevent public access. Larsen leases the Castle from the Thomas Glover 
Estate and sublets it to the academy. 
</P>
<P>
 "Part of the mystique of the Castle is based on it being a private club, and 
frankly, if it ever came down to a vote, I would be totally against (opening to 
the public)," says Larsen, who is not an academy board member but attends the 
meetings as the club's co-founder. "It would be a tremendous mistake, and I 
really don't think it was ever seriously considered. Certainly, if they got 
that hard up for business there would be other ways to make money." 
</P>
<P>
 But Horwitz and other board members tell a different story, saying that while 
the matter has tentatively been tabled, it is far from concluded. 
</P>
<P>
 "I have to be honest with you. That's something that we have been discussing 
and we've had debates on it until we were blue in the face," Horwitz says. "We 
have not acquiesced to that as yet, only because one of the things that has 
kept the Castle going is the mystique and part of the mystique is that you 
absolutely cannot come unless you are the guest of a member." 
</P>
<P>
 Blackstone, citing the same mystique, said he too would oppose opening the 
club to the public and claimed the matter had not come up since he joined the 
academy board in January. But he also made it clear that he would "not discuss 
the business of the board outside of the board. We're all given to keeping 
secrets in the world of magic. They're like secrets in the military; you only 
tell those with a need to know." 
</P>
<P>
 Still, Horwitz expects the matter to come up again at some point. 
</P>
<P>
 "There has been no final decision, but we have not closed our minds to it," he 
says. "I would be willing, personally, to try it for a limited period of time 
and see whether it works or not, but I haven't polled the rest of the board 
because we discussed it in a different context and we've not come to a decision 
on it." 
</P>
<P>
 In the meantime, the changes in the Castle's approach to doing business have 
not affected its vaunted status among magicians, who gather nightly to exchange 
tips, watch each other's acts, or just study the art of magic in the Castle's 
20,000-book library. 
</P>
<P>
 "There are so many magicians there, and there (is) a good stable of reference 
material to work with," says magician Gillis. "I go there and see guys with 
different types of gimmicks -- guys who invented different tricks. They're like 
magic nerds, guys that invent very creative magic presentations and effects, 
and they're real creative-genius types, so it's a pretty neat place to make 
contacts." 
</P>
<P>
 If anything, Gillis says, the acts are consistently better since changes were 
made to the booking policies.  
</P>
<P>
 "They've gotten more conscientious lately about booking better acts," Gillis 
says. "A lot of times in the past there might have been some situations where, 
'This guy's a real nice guy. He's a member. He has a good personality. Let's 
give him a week.' I think they're more concerned about the caliber of performer 
now. The last three times I've been there, there have been some dynamite acts." 
</P>
<P>
 The academy still operates a youth organization that gives children the chance 
to perform with and be critiqued by top-name magicians. In addition, a $30,000 
expansion to the Castle's basement is nearly complete, dedicated to performance 
art and featuring collectibles such as Jimmy Durante's breakaway piano and the 
bar from "Hello, Dolly." 
</P>
<P>
 Davis, the Castle's general manager, says the new emphasis on good business 
will not mean the club will stray from its original goal of teaching and 
promoting magic. He also admits that as a non-magician, it can be difficult to 
run a business that is not 100% dedicated to turning a profit. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've been approached by people all over the world to create another Magic 
Castle, but I'm a bottom-line kind of guy, and this place just doesn't work" 
strictly as a business proposition, Davis said. "It's the love of magic that 
makes it go, so while you're compelled to make decisions for a business reason, 
every time you make a move you do so in consideration of the membership. This 
wasn't intended to be a money-making expedition." 
</P>
<P>
 None of the Castle's 75 employees were laid off during last year's revamping, 
and Davis says he now hopes to expand by importing more acts from Europe and 
launching a series of instructional seminars that would travel throughout the 
United States as part of the current membership drive. The academy has also 
established an executive committee of magician and associate members, asking 
them to review all Castle policies and provide opinions on offering perks such 
as free dinners for members on their birthdays. 
</P>
<P>
 "Frankly, what we must do and are dedicated to doing is to increase the 
pleasure of the membership," says Horwitz, who notes he is investigating 
whether the IRS will classify member dues as tax-deductible. "For a long time, 
with the Castle short of money, they didn't cut anything but they didn't do 
anything, either. We want to try to run the club as a business, but keep the 
thought in mind that you increase that business by making the membership very 
happy." 
</P>
<P>
 Thanks to the Castle's legendary status, happy is what they seem to be. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's probably the nicest place to showcase in the L.A. area," Gillis says. 
"It's nationally famous because it's the only place of its kind, and in the 
magic community it's ultra-famous." 
</P>
<P>
 Sums up Blackstone, whose father's name is bestowed on one of the Castle's 
rooms: "It's really the lifeblood of all the hobbyists and the professionals in 
magic." 
</P>
</TEXT>
