<TEXT>
<P>
 EXTREMISM: A former Israeli chief rabbi, interpreting Jewish law, commanded 
Jews on Wednesday to assassinate PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat (A4). That's not, 
however, likely to be the way most religious experts see things. . . . "It is 
not at all reflective of Jewish law," said Rabbi Moshe Rothblum of Adat Ari El 
synagogue in North Hollywood. "Unfortunately, there are extremists on all 
sides." 
</P>
<P>
 BOND BUMMER: Pierce Brosnan is the new James Bond, which many people think is 
a perfect fit. But there are plenty of Bond die-hards who don't like it. "He 
reminds me of a Roger Moore type," said Danny Biederman of Calabasas, who even 
named his son, Bond, after 007. "He's not as forceful and serious as Sean 
Connery or Timothy Dalton." 
</P>
<P>
 ONE MORE STOP: Emilee Klein (above), a Notre Dame High graduate, better learn 
what to do after winning golf tournaments. It's likely to happen pretty often. 
Klein, 19, just finished her career at Arizona State with an NCAA Division I 
title, and will now try to make the pros. . . . One way of celebrating Klein 
won't do is chuck the ball into the gallery. "I can't throw," she said (C12). 
</P>
<P>
 NOT FANTASTIC: The NBA Finals began Wednesday night (C1), but one Valley hoop 
expert who isn't too thrilled about the current brand of pro basketball is 
Encino's John Wooden. Wooden, who stressed finesse at UCLA, doesn't approve of 
all the shoving near the post. . . . "The game has become too physical," he 
said, "and it's taken something away from the beauty of it. I've been worried 
for some time." 
</P>
<P>
 SAVING HISTORY: With all the D-day hoopla, the world was reminded this week of 
war heroes and noble causes. But Bruce Herman doesn't need any reminders. His 
Chatsworth office is filled with military memorabilia, including a rare drum 
from the Civil War and Prussian generals' helmets. He started collecting at 10, 
and is still going strong. . . . "Somebody has to be the caretaker of it," 
Herman says (B2). Michael Arkush 
</P>
