<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: GRANADA HILLS; HOSPITAL RECEIVES SPECIAL RECOGNITION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF SCHNAUFER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A team of specialists at Granada Hills Community Hospital will be honored by 
the Alzheimer's Assn., the first time a San Fernando Valley hospital has 
received the group's special recognition award. 
</P>
<P>
 The award, which was announced Wednesday, will honor the hospital's Center for 
Aging Research and Evaluation (CARE). The ninth annual award will be presented 
at the association's award luncheon Friday in Beverly Hills. 
</P>
<P>
 Peter Braun, executive director of the group's Los Angeles chapter, said the 
hospital's CARE unit is "the key link in providing care for Alzheimer's 
patients and family members in the Valley." 
</P>
<P>
 The Alzheimer's Assn., which has 227 chapters nationwide, is the largest 
national voluntary health organization dedicated to researching the causes, 
prevention and cure of the disease. It also provides support to families of 
Alzheimer's victims. 
</P>
<P>
 An estimated 150,000 people in Los Angeles County suffer from Alzheimer's 
disease, a progressive dementia that ultimately leads to death, association 
leaders said. 
</P>
<P>
 The Granada Hills hospital and its CARE unit also are being recognized, Braun 
said, "for their special efforts in dealing with the care of the elderly in the 
North Valley following the earthquake." 
</P>
<P>
 After the Jan. 17 Northridge temblor, the CARE team contacted its patients and 
families to determine if they needed assistance and offered emergency referral 
services to all elderly in the Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 The CARE team is made up of two neurologists, a geriatrician, a psychiatrist 
and several nurses and clerical staff. 
</P>
<P>
 Daily services, many of which are free, include initial assessment of dementia 
patients, as well as the CARE Club -- a twice-weekly program featuring social 
interaction and exercise for early-stage patients. Four support groups help 
care-givers cope with their roles. 
</P>
<P>
 The CARE program is seeking patient volunteers for clinical trials with new 
medications in the hopes they will benefit those with Alzheimer's disease. 
Volunteers receive free medical care and evaluation during the program. JEFF 
SCHNAUFER 
</P>
</TEXT>
