<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA / ANTELOPE VALLEY; FARES COULD INCREASE FOR BUS SERVICE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHARON MOESER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Using public transportation in and around the Antelope Valley may soon be 
slightly more costly. 
</P>
<P>
 The Antelope Valley Transit Authority is considering raising its fare on local 
routes from 75 cents to 80 cents. A public hearing on the proposed rate 
increase is slated for July 25, although transit officials do not expect much 
protest because the rate hikes are so minimal. 
</P>
<P>
 Citing the controversy that has erupted since the Los Angeles County 
Metropolitan Transit Authority proposed raising its fares to make up for six 
years without increases, Bill Budlong, AVTA executive director, said he 
believes it's better to impose small increases on a regular basis. 
</P>
<P>
 Kurt Mills, AVTA administrative analyst, said, "We want to do rate hikes that 
are on a timely basis. There's been other transportation agencies that have 
waited years and to catch up with their costs the rate hikes have been real 
dramatic. 
</P>
<P>
 "Going from 75 to 80 cents is nothing." 
</P>
<P>
 Other rates would also increase slightly. 
</P>
<P>
 Reduced fares for elderly and disabled riders on the local buses are slated to 
go from 35 cents to 40 cents. Monthly passes for the general public would 
increase $1 to $21, although those for seniors and the disabled will remain the 
same. 
</P>
<P>
 The transit agency is proposing no change for its door-to-door Dial-a-Ride 
service for seniors and the disabled, and for its medical shuttle that 
transports residents to major hospitals and medical centers in the Los Angeles 
basin. 
</P>
<P>
 AVTA commuter fares to Downtown Los Angeles and the San Fernando Valley would 
increase $1, to $7 and $6, respectively. A 20-ride pass on the downtown line 
will go up $5, to $105 and a 44-ride pass to the San Fernando Valley would go 
up $5, to $125. Monthly passes for seniors and the disabled would not rise. 
</P>
<P>
 AVTA is not proposing any changes to the fares on its Van Nuys or Century City 
commuter lines, which were initiated with federal funds after the Jan. 17 
Northridge quake crippled Southern California freeways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
