<P>
 MEXICAN STOCKS 
</P>
<P>
 * Mexican stocks declined for the second straight session. Continuing 
nervousness about the Mexican election has kept interest rates high, which in 
turn make credit more expensive and hurt corporate earnings. 
</P>
<P>
 * Telmex shares trading in New York fell $1 to $61.25 and local Series L 
shares fell 0.16 pesos to 10.24. The company's shares declined in part because 
executives of Grupo Iusacell, a competitor for Mexico's phone market, are 
making a series of presentations to investors. Iusacell, in a joint venture 
with Bell Atlantic and Grupo Financiero Banamex Accival and partner MCI, are 
among those who plan to challenge Telmex when the long-distance market opens up 
in 1997.  
</P>
<P>
 Source: Times Wire Services SPOTLIGHT: COLOMBIA 
</P>
<P>
 Colombians will go to the polls June 19 to decide between two presidential 
candidates whose main differences are economic: whether to continue current 
free-market programs or make adjustments to protect certain sectors. An 
economic program to stop poppy production for the illegal drug trade appears to 
be faltering. 
</P>
