<HEADLINE>
<P>
BEHIND THE SCENES: MAKING WAVES ON SOLID GROUND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROSE APODACA JONES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Say ball and what usually comes to mind are socialites amid sophisticated 
revelry or, at the very least, Cinderella. But when the ball involves a bunch 
of beach-bred dudes, spike all expectations. 
</P>
<P>
 In this high society, superiority is determined by who dominates the waves, 
and it's the boards that have become sophisticated. 
</P>
<P>
 In the name of a good cause and good fun, members of the surf industry suited 
up for the fifth annual Waterman's Ball at the California Scenario Sculpture 
Garden in Costa Mesa on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 Sponsored by the Surf Industry Manufacturers Assn., the event drew hundreds of 
surf designers, company owners, artists and distributors, as well as supporters 
of the Surfrider Foundation, American Oceans Campaign and the Orange County 
Marine Institute, which benefited from the gala.  
</P>
<P>
 The code was creative black tie, but even that was a stretch for some, such as 
Quiksilver VP Danny Kwock who attended in a cotton aloha shirt and jeans. It 
was, he said, in honor of filmmaker Bruce ("The Endless Summer") Brown, who 
received the Waterman Achievement Award that night. 
</P>
<P>
 Glass slippers? 
</P>
<P>
 Try Converse sneakers, sports sandals and even thongs paired with pin-stripe 
suits and tuxedos. Katin co-owner Bill Sharp and Surfer magazine artist Joe 
McElroy hot-footed it in red suede creepers. 
</P>
<P>
 McElroy also shared World Jungle owner Jack Denny's penchant for polyester -- 
in a sickly shade of chocolate. Dudes also got the opportunity to let loose by 
wrapping up in sarongs, both in primitive prints and in classier black satin. 
</P>
<P>
 As for the women, outrageous black cocktail dresses in sheers and detailed 
with cutouts competed for attention with barely-there baby dolls in whites and 
metallics. There was also a barrage of ocean blue sequins and Barbie get-ups.  
</P>
<P>
 The Hawaiian print tux accouterments and fresh flower leis aside, the best 
accessory of the night was attached to display artist Raggs Adams suit jacket 
lapel: a sticker that read simply "Cool Guy." ROSE APODACA JONES 
</P>
</TEXT>
