<DOCID> 049901 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
June 9, 1994, Thursday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
OC Live; Page 5; OC Live 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
182 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLASSIC OF THE WEEK: ROY ELDRIDGE WITH THE GENE KRUPA ORCHESTRA FEATURING ANITA 
O'DAY "UPTOWN" (1941-49) COLUMBIA  
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BUDDY SEIGAL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Trumpeter Eldridge, drummer Krupa and singer O'Day number among the giants, so 
it's no surprise that the hot licks abound on these recordings -- even if the 
material is more commercial pop/swing than real jazz. 
</P>
<P>
 Still, even if they did play their most important and enduring work elsewhere, 
it's nonetheless a pleasure to hear these three together, particularly the 
exchanges between O'Day and Eldridge as she exhorts him to "blow, man, blow!" 
and enthuses "root, and solid to boot!" (Note should be taken that such close 
work between a white female and a black male was in and of itself something of 
a watershed in '40s Amer ica.)Light-years ahead of his time and second only to 
Louis Armstrong in terms of pre-bop influence, Eldridge plays beautiful upper 
register solos that sing and sear (check out his especially lyrical rendition 
of "Rockin' Chair"). 
</P>
<P>
 O'Day, meanwhile, gives glimpses of her true talent for scat singing with hip, 
restrained phrasing even on the corniest material. And Krupa, always incredibly 
powerful, thunders like a tommy gun throughout. BUDDY SEIGAL 
</P>
</TEXT>
